==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*lagjan-'', a causative form of ''*ligjan-'' (Old English [[licgan]]), from Indo-European ''*legh-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[ledza]], Old Saxon [[leggian]] (Dutch [[leggen]]), Old High German [[leggen]] (German [[legen]]), Old Norse [[leggja]] (Swedish [[lägga]]), Gothic [[𐌻𐌰𐌲𐌾𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[λεκτρον]], Latin [[lectus]] ‘bed’, Celtic ''*leg-'' (Old Irish [[lige]], Irish [[luighe]]), Slavic ''*ležati'' (Russian [[лежать]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'leʤan/

===Verb===
'''lecgan''' (class 1 weak)
# to [[lay]], to bring down, to [[prostrate]]
# to [[lay]] or [[place]] in a position of rest; to [[bury]] (a person)
#:''Se cyng lægde hi wið Eadward kyng hire hlaforde'': the king laid her by King Edward her lord.
# to [[lay]] (an egg)
#:''Ægru lecgan'': to lay eggs.

